I appreciate the honest critique. Looking at the comic, I think I probably should have arranged it differently. The first 2 panels are the funniest, and probably should have been put last, and the middle one was perhaps too similar in topic (the topics read pajamas, pajamas, social skills, and would have flowed better with a different topic in the middle).
I'm a self-taught cartoonist and always trying to improve. Some of my comics are funny, some may not be. Between being a "student" of comics, and the subjective nature of comedy, that is bound to happen, and I'm aware not everyone will like my work. Nonetheless, as someone interested in learning, I'm always open to constructive critique, so thank you.
Edit: an imaginary boss would also have been hilarious.
Edit 2: I forgot to address the art. I try to avoid what Watterson referred to as "talking heads" and use interesting backgrounds/props when possible. That being said, I think the first 2 panels work best with simple backgrounds that don't distract the eye. The third panel, though, may have worked better if she was shown in a messy room.

I second all the above advice. Also, remember that, just like chocolate cake, no matter how good your comics are, there will always be people that don't like them. Learn from constructive criticism, but don't pay attention to trolls.
Lastly, one thing I'm really glad I've done is keep a notebook that functions as a journal/idea book. It's really cool to flip back and see your original notes on a comic that did well, and seeing what was going on in your life/thoughts at that time as well (and I find it's easier to focus on paper rather than in Word).
